Question 7.1

Describe a situation or problem from your job, everyday life, current events, etc., for which exponential smoothing would be appropriate. What data would you need? Would you expect the value of alpha (the first smoothing parameter) to be closer to 0 or 1, and why?

I am a cloud architect by profession and one of the things that I need to do on a regular basis is to work with my customers on their existing footprint and their near-term, long-term resource requirements to come up with a TCO model. Using exponential smoothing I can forecast their near term requirements and come up with a TCO model to prove the economies of scale of the cloud. I would need the following data * resource type (vcpu, ram, ssd etc), * amount of usage by the hour * seasonal spikes based on customer industry

The alpha value will be closer to 1,for an already established business, due to less variance in their resource consumption and growth It will be closer to 0 for an unregulated, new, upcoming business.

(Part of the point of this assignment is for you to think about how you might use exponential smoothing to answer this question. Feel free to combine it with other models if youd like to. Theres certainly more than one reasonable approach.) Note: in R, you can use either HoltWinters (simpler to use) or the smooth packages es function (harder to use, but more general). If you use es, the Holt-Winters model uses model=AAM in the function call (the first and second constants are used Additively, and the third (seasonality) is used Multiplicatively; the documentation doesnt make that clear).

The weather trend seems to be increasing with the timeseries, hence the time series has a multiplicative seasonality. However seasonality seems to have little effect here considering summers are always high and winters are low. Hence lets fit a model with and without considering seasonality

# fit a multiplicative seasonal exponential smoothing model
model <- HoltWinters(weatherts_train, gamma=NULL, seasonal = "mult", beta=FALSE)
test.fit<-predict(model,n.ahead = length(weatherts_test))
#calculate the RMSE 
rmse_val <- rmse(weatherts_test,test.fit)
printf(" RMSE = %s",rmse_val)
## [1] " RMSE = 19.937780676186"

An RMSE of 19, though fitting a non-seasonal model lowers the RMSE, it is incorrect to fit a non-seasonal model here as we know the data we have is infact seasonal. Lets use it to forecast the summer days of 2016

fit_complete <- HoltWinters(weatherts, gamma=NULL, seasonal = "mult",beta=FALSE)

Apply cusum method to find out if the unofficial summer end has moved further. Repurposing the cusum method from Homework3

cusum_weather <- function(weatherdata) {
#Calculate the mean for the summer months July, August and 15 days of september first 77 rows
weathermeans<-colMeans(weatherdata[1:77,-1])
summermean<-mean(weathermeans)

#Calculate the standard deviation for the summer months July, August and 15 days of september first 77 rows
Sdmatrix<- apply(weatherdata[1:77,-1],2,sd)
meanSd<-mean(Sdmatrix)

#we are trying to find when unofficial summer ends,i.e. decreasing change, so St=max(0,S{t-1}+(mu-xt-C))

#Calculate Xt-Mu for every year
xt_mu<-apply(weatherdata[,-1],1,'-',weathermeans)

#reverse signs i.e. mu-Xt since we are tracking decrease
mu_xt <- (apply(xt_mu,1,'*',-1))

#Lets set C = 0.5 of SD
C<-Sdmatrix*0.5

# subract C 
mu_xt_c <-apply(mu_xt,1,'-',C)
mu_xt_c<-t(mu_xt_c)

#dimensions of the matrix for declaring St matrix
m<-dim(mu_xt)[1]
n<-dim(mu_xt)[2]

#St matrix declaration
St<-matrix(rep(0),nrow=m,ncol=n)

#Calculate St, cusum
for( j in 1:n){
  St_1<-0
  for(i in 1:m){
    St_1<- max(0,St_1+as.numeric(mu_xt_c[i,j]))
    St[i,j]<-St_1
  }
}

#set column names and also append the "day of the month" information
colnames(St)<-colnames(weatherdata[,-1])
St<-cbind(as.matrix(weatherdata[,1]),St)

colnames(St)[1] <- "Day"

#Lets choose an Threshold of 7 * Standard Deviation

Thold<-(Sdmatrix * 7)

#Find unofficial summer ends for each year
summermat<-matrix(nrow=2,ncol=n)
dim(summermat)
colnames(summermat)<-colnames(weatherdata[,-1])

#recalculate the dimensions
ms<-dim(St)[1]
ns<-dim(St)[2]

#Find the tip-over point i.e. the change in temperature for every year
# go column by column, i.e. year by year
for (j in 2:ns){
  
# go row by row, i.e. day by day  
  for(i in 1:ms){
    dayVal<-as.numeric(St[i,j])
    Th<-Thold[j-1]
    if( dayVal > Th ) {
      
      summermat[1,j-1]<- St[i,1]
      summermat[2,j-1]<- weatherdata[i,j]
      break
    }
      
  }
}
    
# When Summer unofficially ends 
summermat<-t(summermat)
colnames(summermat)<-c("Day","Temperature")
return(summermat)
}

Lets look at forecasting using ARIMA.

arima_model<-auto.arima(weatherts_train)
test.fit<-predict(arima_model,n.ahead = length(weatherts_test))

printf("RMSE Arima = %s", rmse(weatherts_test,test.fit$pred))
## [1] "RMSE Arima = 7.10294594049641"

RMSE of 7.1, hence much better accuracy than Holtwinters. Lets find out what the fitted value for 2016 look like

arima_model<-auto.arima(weatherts)

f2016_arima<- predict(arima_model, n.ahead=123 , prediction.interval = TRUE)
